{"id":14880760,"mediaExerciseId":"a373d7f3-3e17-4d0a-8b55-ce148e27f27e","exerciseName":"9","chapterName":"2","chapterTitle":"Financial Statements, Taxes, and Cash Flow","groupId":612265,"groupTitle":"Questions and Problems","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":43,"solutions":[{"id":5901596,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"This exercise requires us to compute for the cash flow to shareholders of Kerber's Tennis Shop","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"Let's first define cash flow to shareholders \n\n**Cash flow to Shareholders** is the amount of money that passes to shareholders in the form of dividends after new equity is deducted","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"Cash Flow to Shareholders is computed as follows:\n\n$$ \\begin{aligned}\n\\text{Cash Flow to Shareholders} &= \\text{Dividends Paid} - {\\text{Net New Equity raised}}\\\\[1pt]\n\\end{aligned}$$","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"Let's identify the given amounts in the problem.\n\n| | 2017| 2018| \n|--|--:|--:| \n| Common Stock| $650,000|$805,000  | \n|Additional Paid-in Surplus |3,980,000|4,200,000| \n| Cash Dividends | | 545,000| \n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":66,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/18/c79b218354aea7f94a365ac5c05a3863/de08eac37d12916efc060d53da1fb9a5/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/18/c79b218354aea7f94a365ac5c05a3863/de08eac37d12916efc060d53da1fb9a5/lateximg.png","width":500}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"Before we compute for the cash flow to shareholders, we need to compute first the net new equity raised using the formula below:\n\n$$\\begin {array}{lrr}\n\\text{Common Stock 2018}&\\$\\hspace{10pt}\\text{805,000}\\\\\n\\text{Additional Paid-in Surplus }&\\underline{\\text{4,200,000}}&\\text{\\$\\hspace{5pt}\n5,005,000}\\\\\n\\text{Common Stock 2017}&\\text{650,000}\\\\\n\\text{Additional Paid-in Surplus }&\\underline{\\text{3,980,000}}&\\underline{\\text{\n4,630,000}}\\\\\n\\textbf{Net New Equity raised}&&\\underline{\\underline{\\$\\hspace{5pt}\\textbf{375,000}}}\\\\\n\\end{array}$$\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":103,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/18/c79b218354aea7f94a365ac5c05a3863/50c74c5f608a8c82e7c7967d10bce118/lateximg_large.png","width":1055},"regular":{"height":53,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/18/c79b218354aea7f94a365ac5c05a3863/50c74c5f608a8c82e7c7967d10bce118/lateximg.png","width":528}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5},{"columns":[{"text":"Now that we have computed the net new equity raised, let's now compute for the cash flow to shareholders using the equation in step 3.\n\n$$ \\begin{aligned}\n\\text{Cash Flow to Shareholders} &= \\text{Dividends Paid} - {\\text{Net New Equity raised}}\\\\[5pt]\n&= \\text{\\$545,000} - {\\text{375,000}}\\\\[5pt]\n&= \\underline{\\underline{\\textbf{\\$170,000}}}\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\nTherefore, the cash flow to shareholders of Kerber's Tennis Shop is **$170,000**.\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":132,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/18/c79b218354aea7f94a365ac5c05a3863/19a15f08f44a0beeaf4dba3b8e1ff473/lateximg_large.png","width":943},"regular":{"height":68,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/18/c79b218354aea7f94a365ac5c05a3863/19a15f08f44a0beeaf4dba3b8e1ff473/lateximg.png","width":472}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":6}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"0836dec4-9e52-4519-bbcb-fbf74536b4e2","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":6}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14880761,"exerciseName":"10","page":44,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"8a814dc3-58f5-465e-b51c-c857e57877e4","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-2-questions-and-problems-10-8a814dc3-58f5-465e-b51c-c857e57877e4"},{"id":14880762,"exerciseName":"11","page":44,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"87ff7e02-7747-492f-ac16-126d40ccf78a","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-2-questions-and-problems-11-87ff7e02-7747-492f-ac16-126d40ccf78a"}],"previousExercises":[{"id":14880759,"exerciseName":"8","page":43,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"edb30281-ba18-49ee-80c3-e275b0df7697","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-2-questions-and-problems-8-edb30281-ba18-49ee-80c3-e275b0df7697"},{"id":14880758,"exerciseName":"7","page":43,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"8328b85b-f872-4963-9a3a-7008aaa7deef","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundam